How applying SOLID principles to your error handling strategy can transform your Android codebase from fragile to resilient.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Every Android developer has been there. You open a file and find a 200-line try-catch block wrapping half your business logic. Error messages are hardcoded. The same retry logic is copied and pasted across 15 different repositories. Your ViewModel knows about HTTP status codes, database exceptions, and somehow even JSONException.
It doesn’t have to be this way.
After years of building production Android apps, I’ve found that the same SOLID principles we apply to feature development can radically improve how we handle errors. In this article, we’ll build a complete core-error module from scratch, one you can drop into any project and see how each SOLID principle shapes its design.

The Problem: Error Handling as an Afterthought
Most Android projects start with something like this:
class UserViewModel(private val api: ApiService) : ViewModel() { fun loadUser(id: String) {
viewModelScope.launch {
try {
val user = api.getUser(id)
_state.value = UserState.Success(user)
} catch (e: HttpException) {
if (e.code() == 401) {
_state.value = UserState.Error("Session expired. Please login again.")
} else if (e.code() == 404) {
_state.value = UserState.Error("User not found.")
} else {
_state.value = UserState.Error("Something went wrong.")
}
} catch (e: IOException) {
_state.value = UserState.Error("No internet connection.")
} catch (e: Exception) {
_state.value = UserState.Error("An unexpected error occurred.")
}
}
}
}
This works until you have 30 screens doing the same thing. Then someone decides error messages need localization. Then the product team wants retry buttons for network errors, but not for auth errors. Then you need analytics for each error type.
Suddenly, your “simple” error handling is a maintenance nightmare.
What we need is a dedicated core-error module a standalone, reusable library that centralizes error modeling, mapping, and handling. Let’s build one, one SOLID principle at a time.

The Architecture: Where Does core-error Sit?
Before we write code, let’s understand the dependency graph:
Presentation → Domain → core-error
Data → core-errorcore-error is a leaf module. It depends on nothing from your app. Your domain layer uses its models (AppError, AppResult) the same way it would use Kotlin's own Result type; they're just sealed interfaces and data classes. Your data layer uses its mapping utilities. Your presentation layer uses its action types.
This is intentional. Error modeling is a cross-cutting concern, and it belongs in its own module.

S — Single Responsibility: Separate What Went Wrong from What to Show
The first and most impactful decision: your domain layer should describe what happened. Your presentation layer should decide what to show. These are two different responsibilities, and they should never live in the same class.
The Error Model
We define a sealed hierarchy that represents every failure our app can encounter:
sealed interface AppError { sealed interface Network : AppError {
data object NoConnection : Network
data object Timeout : Network
data class Server(val code: Int, val serverMessage: String? = null) : Network
}
sealed interface Auth : AppError {
data object SessionExpired : Auth
data object Unauthorized : Auth
}
sealed interface Data : AppError {
data class NotFound(val resource: String) : Data
data class Validation(val fields: Map<String, String>) : Data
}
data class Unknown(val throwable: Throwable) : AppError
}
Notice what’s not here: no UI strings, no “show toast vs. snackbar” decisions, no retry logic. This model purely describes the failure domain. A Network.NoConnection error means the same thing whether it's displayed in a dialog, a banner, or logged silently.
The Result Wrapper
Instead of throwing exceptions across layers, we wrap outcomes explicitly:
sealed interface AppResult<out T> {
data class Success<T>(val data: T) : AppResult<T>
data class Failure(val error: AppError) : AppResult<Nothing>
}This forces every consumer to acknowledge the failure path. No more “I forgot to wrap this call in try-catch” bugs.
Localization-Ready Text
For the presentation layer to do its job, we need a type that can carry either a raw string or a string resource:
sealed interface UiText {
data class Raw(val value: String) : UiText
data class Resource(@StringRes val resId: Int, val args: List<Any> = emptyList()) : UiText fun resolve(context: Context): String = when (this) {
is Raw -> value
is Resource -> context.getString(resId, *args.toTypedArray())
}
}
And the action type that tells the UI layer what to do:
sealed interface ErrorAction {
data class ShowMessage(val message: UiText) : ErrorAction
data class Navigate(val route: String) : ErrorAction
data class Retry(val message: UiText, val retryAction: suspend () -> Unit) : ErrorAction
data object Silent : ErrorAction
}Each type has exactly one responsibility. AppError describes what went wrong. UiText handles localization. ErrorAction tells the UI what to do. No class does two things.

O — Open/Closed: Extend Without Modifying
Here’s the real-world scenario: your app uses Retrofit today. Next quarter, one team migrates to Ktor. The quarter after that, someone adds a GraphQL layer. Each framework throws different exceptions. Do you keep adding catch blocks to your mapper every time?
No. You design for extension without modification.
The Plugin System
We define a simple plugin interface:
interface ExceptionMapperPlugin {
fun map(throwable: Throwable): AppError?
}Return an AppError if you can handle this exception; return null to pass it to the next plugin. Classic chain-of-responsibility.
The Core Mapper
The ExceptionMapper accepts a set of plugins and falls back to built-in defaults:
@Singleton
class ExceptionMapper @Inject constructor(
private val customMappers: Set<@JvmSuppressWildcards ExceptionMapperPlugin>
) { fun map(throwable: Throwable): AppError {
for (plugin in customMappers) {
plugin.map(throwable)?.let { return it }
}
return mapDefault(throwable)
}
private fun mapDefault(throwable: Throwable): AppError = when (throwable) {
is SocketTimeoutException -> AppError.Network.Timeout
is IOException -> AppError.Network.NoConnection
else -> AppError.Unknown(throwable)
}
}
A Retrofit Plugin
The built-in Retrofit plugin uses reflection so that Retrofit remains a compileOnly dependency the module works even if the consumer doesn't use Retrofit:
class RetrofitExceptionMapperPlugin @Inject constructor() : ExceptionMapperPlugin { override fun map(throwable: Throwable): AppError? {
val httpExceptionClass = try {
Class.forName("retrofit2.HttpException")
} catch (_: ClassNotFoundException) {
return null
}
if (!httpExceptionClass.isInstance(throwable)) return null
val code = httpExceptionClass.getMethod("code").invoke(throwable) as Int
val message = httpExceptionClass.getMethod("message").invoke(throwable) as? String
return mapHttpCode(code, message)
}
private fun mapHttpCode(code: Int, message: String?): AppError = when (code) {
401 -> AppError.Auth.SessionExpired
403 -> AppError.Auth.Unauthorized
404 -> AppError.Data.NotFound("resource")
in 500..599 -> AppError.Network.Server(code, message)
else -> AppError.Network.Server(code, message)
}
}
Adding a New Plugin
When the GraphQL team shows up, they don’t touch any existing code. They write one class in their own module:
class GraphQLExceptionMapperPlugin @Inject constructor() : ExceptionMapperPlugin {
override fun map(throwable: Throwable): AppError? {
if (throwable !is GraphQLException) return null
return when (throwable.errorType) {
"UNAUTHENTICATED" -> AppError.Auth.SessionExpired
"NOT_FOUND" -> AppError.Data.NotFound(throwable.path)
else -> AppError.Unknown(throwable)
}
}
}And register it via Hilt:
@Module
@InstallIn(SingletonComponent::class)
abstract class GraphQLErrorModule {
@Binds @IntoSet
abstract fun bindGraphQLMapper(impl: GraphQLExceptionMapperPlugin): ExceptionMapperPlugin
}Zero lines changed in core-error. The module is closed for modification, open for extension.
Result Extensions
The same principle applies to our AppResult type. We add behavior through extension functions, not by modifying the sealed interface:
inline fun <T> AppResult<T>.onSuccess(action: (T) -> Unit): AppResult<T> {
if (this is AppResult.Success) action(data)
return this
}inline fun <T> AppResult<T>.onFailure(action: (AppError) -> Unit): AppResult<T> {
if (this is AppResult.Failure) action(error)
return this
}
inline fun <T, R> AppResult<T>.map(transform: (T) -> R): AppResult<R> = when (this) {
is AppResult.Success -> AppResult.Success(transform(data))
is AppResult.Failure -> this
}
inline fun <T, R> AppResult<T>.flatMap(transform: (T) -> AppResult<R>): AppResult<R> = when (this) {
is AppResult.Success -> transform(data)
is AppResult.Failure -> this
}
inline fun <T> AppResult<T>.recover(transform: (AppError) -> AppResult<T>): AppResult<T> = when (this) {
is AppResult.Success -> this
is AppResult.Failure -> transform(error)
}
fun <T> AppResult<T>.getOrNull(): T? = when (this) {
is AppResult.Success -> data
is AppResult.Failure -> null
}
fun <T> AppResult<T>.getOrDefault(default: T): T = when (this) {
is AppResult.Success -> data
is AppResult.Failure -> default
}
Any team can add their own extensions without touching the module:
// Analytics team adds this in their own module
fun <T> AppResult<T>.trackFailure(analytics: Analytics): AppResult<T> =
onFailure { error ->
analytics.track("error", mapOf("type" to error::class.simpleName))
}
L — Liskov Substitution: Every Handler Must Honour the Contract
The Liskov Substitution Principle says that subtypes must be substitutable for their base types without breaking behaviour. In error handling, this means: if you define an ErrorHandler interface, every implementation must fully handle the error, not silently swallow it or half-handle it.
The Contract
interface ErrorHandler {
fun handle(error: AppError): ErrorAction
}The return type is ErrorAction, not ErrorAction?. Every implementation must return a meaningful action. You can't return null. You can't throw. You can't half-handle.
The Default Implementation
class DefaultErrorHandler @Inject constructor(
private val globalErrorHandler: GlobalErrorHandler
) : ErrorHandler { override fun handle(error: AppError): ErrorAction = when (error) {
is AppError.Network.NoConnection -> ErrorAction.ShowMessage(
UiText.Raw("No internet connection. Please check your network.")
)
is AppError.Network.Timeout -> ErrorAction.ShowMessage(
UiText.Raw("Request timed out. Please try again.")
)
is AppError.Network.Server -> ErrorAction.ShowMessage(
UiText.Raw("Server error (${error.code}). Please try again later.")
)
is AppError.Auth.SessionExpired -> ErrorAction.Navigate("login")
is AppError.Auth.Unauthorized -> ErrorAction.ShowMessage(
UiText.Raw("You don't have permission to perform this action.")
)
is AppError.Data.NotFound -> ErrorAction.ShowMessage(
UiText.Raw("Requested ${error.resource} was not found.")
)
is AppError.Data.Validation -> ErrorAction.ShowMessage(
UiText.Raw(formatValidationErrors(error.fields))
)
is AppError.Unknown -> ErrorAction.ShowMessage(
UiText.Raw("An unexpected error occurred.")
)
}
private fun formatValidationErrors(fields: Map<String, String>): String =
fields.entries.joinToString("\n") { (field, message) -> "$field: $message" }
}
Because AppError is a sealed hierarchy, the Kotlin compiler enforces that every branch is handled. If you add a new AppError subtype next month, every when expression breaks at compile time. No silent failures. No missed cases.
Any screen that needs custom error handling can provide its own ErrorHandler implementation. As long as it returns a valid ErrorAction for every AppError, it's a valid substitute. Liskov would be proud.

I — Interface Segregation: Don’t Force Everyone to Handle Everything
Not every layer needs to handle every error type. A
